Wrenbury Village
[trigger none]
[vignette dungeons/wrenbury]

The market smells like meat pies and warm beer, which is to say it smells like every market. A vendor works a portable clay oven, pulling pies with a flat paddle and handing them off in squares of waxed cloth. Next to him, a woman fills cups of small beer from a cask that's seen better days. Neither of them is selling anything related to the battle. They're selling lunch, and lunch is eternal.

The blankets start past the food. One displays a careful grid of spearheads and arrowpoints, all of them pitted and brown with rust, laid out on dark cloth like a jeweler's display. The seller has written little cards in neat handwriting, labeling each piece by origin and unit, as if provenance makes corroded metal into something worth carrying home. Maybe it does. The next blanket is more personal: buttons, buckles, a dented canteen with something scratched into the side that might be a name. Nobody's written cards for these.

One stall breaks the pattern entirely: Revathi tile fragments, arranged by color, each one a curved shard of deep glaze. Blues and ochres and a green you don't see in imperial work. Genuine, clearly. Wrong battlefield, wrong century, wrong everything, but the seller doesn't seem troubled by that.

At the end of the row, a stall stacked with military histories and map prints. The bookseller sits behind them with the energy of a man who has asked someone not to touch the merchandise so many times that his face has set that way permanently. He watches every hand that comes near with the focus of a hunting dog.

Past him, raised voices.

A young woman is leaning across a blanket at a seated vendor, making a point with the kind of rigid composure that means she's already shouted once and is trying not to again. He's leaning back, palms up, weathering it. A few people have slowed to watch, finding reasons to linger nearby.

She glances at you and her eyes catch on your hand. Your ring. She doesn't call out. Not yet. But she holds your gaze, and you both know the way this works. If you walk over there, you're not a tourist anymore, you're a Guild arbiter.

choices:

* Involve yourself in the argument = See if you can sort this out
  +open "Sera Calloway"

